{{Infobox artist | name = Juan Garaizabal | image = Memoria Urbana Berlin.jpg | image_size = 220 | caption = [[Memoria Urbana Berlin]] | birth_name = Juan Garaizabal Marsans | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1971|3|20}} | birth_place = [[Madrid]], Spain | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = Spanish | field = Sculptor | training = | works = | influenced by = }} '''Juan Garaizabal''' (born 1971 in [[Madrid]]) is a Spanish [[Plastic arts|plastic artist]], Garaizabal's work encompasses drawings, sculpture, [[Light art|light]] and [[Sound sculpture|acoustic installations]], [[video art]], and [[engraving]]. He is internationally known for his [[Monumental sculpture|monumental]] [[Public art|public sculptures]]. His "Urban Memories", structures intertwining sculpture and illumination, are a recuperation of long-lost architectural elements occupying [[Public space|vacant]], historically significant sites.<ref>[http://www.rtve.es/alacarta/videos/telediario/escultor-espanol-juan-garai-zabal-presenta-proyecto-memorias-urbanas/1451945/ TVE (Video)]</ref>
==Artistic history== At 14, Garaizabal entered the IB 67[[Academy figure|drawing academy]] in Madrid where he studied for three years, later graduating from [[Reims Management School|CESEM]] in [[Reims]], France. His early work was split mainly between visual arts and the transforming of sundry spaces into [[loft]]s, a concept formally unknown in Spain. As a [[conceptual art]]ist, a large part of his work has been done by hand, using such techniques as [[forging]], [[carpentry]], electricity, [[plastic arts|plasticity]], and [[masonry]] – all skills acquired through time and experimentation. As of 2008, his main studio is in [[Berlin]], Germany, although he maintains another in [[Madrid]], Spain.
